  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(55) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Being full of the Holy Ghost.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—There is something suggestive in the fact that this description comes at the close, as at the beginning, of the record of St. Stephen’s work (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 6:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). From first to last he had been conspicuous as manifesting the power of the higher life which had, as it were, illumined and transfigured his whole being. The Greek “being full” implies, not a sudden inspiration, but a permanent state.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And saw the glory of God.—Stephen had begun with speaking of “the God of glory” (Acts 7:2). He ends with the vision of that glory as belonging to the Son of Man. The fact was inferred partly, we may believe, from the rapt, fixed expression of the martyr’s face, partly from the words that followed, interpreting that upward gaze. On the word for “looked up steadfastly,” see Note on Acts 3:4.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And saw the glory of God.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Stephen had begun with speaking of “the God of glory” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 7:2",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). He ends with the vision of that glory as belonging to the Son of Man. The fact was inferred partly, we may believe, from the rapt, fixed expression of the martyr’s face, partly from the words that followed, interpreting that upward gaze. On the word for “looked up steadfastly,” see Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 3:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
